ewcommand{\pts}{s}$ For a parameter $\eps \in (0,1)$, we present a new construction of $\eps$-locality-sensitive orderings (<LSOs) in $\Re^d$ of size $M = O(\Eps^{d-1} \log \Eps)$, where $\Eps = 1/\eps$. This improves over previous work by a factor of $\Eps$, and is optimal up to a factor of $\log \Eps$. Such a set of LSOs has the property that for any two points, $\p, \q \in [0,1]^d$, there exist an order in the set such that all the points between $\p$ and $\q$ in the order are $\eps$-close to either $\p$ or $\q$. The existence of such LSOs is a fundamental property of low dimensional Euclidean space, conceptually similar to the existence of well-separated pairs decomposition, so the question of how to compute (near) optimal construction of LSOs is quite natural. As a consequence we get a flotilla of improved dynamic geometric algorithms, such as maintaining bichromatic closest pair, and spanners, among others. In particular, for geometric dynamic spanners the new result matches (up to the aforementioned $\log \Eps$ factor) the lower bound, Thus offering a near-optimal simple dynamic data-structure for maintaining spanners under insertions and deletions.
